										<div class="post_wrapper author">
											<div id="about_the_author">
												<div class="gravatar"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/diarmaidmacculloch/"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/diarmaidmacculloch-100x100.jpeg" width="100" height="100" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/diarmaidmacculloch-300x300.jpeg 2x" alt="Diarmaid MacCulloch" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></a></div>
												<div class="description author withsidebar">
													<h6><a href="https://lithub.com/author/diarmaidmacculloch/">Diarmaid MacCulloch</a></h6>
													Diarmaid MacCulloch is a fellow of St. Cross College, Oxford, and professor of the history of the church at Oxford University. His books include <em>Suffolk and the Tudors</em>, winner of the Royal Historical Society’s Whitfield Prize, and <em>Thomas Cranmer: A Life</em>, which won the Whitbread Biography Prize, the James Tait Black Prize, and the Duff Cooper Prize. A former Anglican deacon, he has presented many highly celebrated documentaries for television and radio, and was knighted in 2012 for his services to scholarship. He lives in Oxford, England.																									</div>
											</div><br class="clear"/><br/>
										</div>

